ííŸ@ca77d40a245100f235f4ad8a64dfe24cbeeaa01b4a6b910529d773acfded7036⁄‘Title: Running System (External) Commands
Path: Running System (External) Commands
Content:
Nu provides a set of commands that you can use across different operating systems ("internal" commands) and having this consistency is helpful when creating cross-platform code. Sometimes, though, you want to run an external command that has the same name as an internal Nu command. To run the external 
[link: /commands/docs/ls.md] ``ls``
 or 
[link: /commands/docs/date.md] ``date``
 command, for example, preface it with the caret (^) sigil. Prefacing with the caret calls the external command found in the user's 
``PATH``
 (e.g. 
``/bin/ls``
) instead of Nu's internal 
[link: /commands/docs/ls.md] ``ls``
 command).
Nu internal command:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
ls

```
External command (typically 
``/usr/bin/ls``
):
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
^ls

```
::: note

On Windows, 
``ls``
 is a PowerShell 
alias
 by default, so 
``^ls``
 will not find a matching system 
command
.

:::
íŸ@1e23b7d6bf12c45200323cc7e27dd65a56d9eb360899a3f626da203be49386cc⁄kTitle: Running System (External) Commands
Path: Additional Windows Notes
Content:
When running an external command on Windows,

Nushell forwards some 
``CMD.EXE``
 internal commands to cmd instead of attempting to run external commands.

[link: coming_from_cmd.md] Coming from CMD.EXE
 contains a list of these commands and describes the behavior in more detail.
